<subSubSection id="C1D410CE5733FFD2FF1BFEDDFE53FC9D" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" type="description">
<paragraph id="897143455733FFD2FF1BFEDDFDA9FEC2" blockId="13.[136,1452,223,826]" box="[189,573,331,358]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF1BFEDDFEE9FEC1" bold="true" box="[189,381,331,358]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Common name:</emphasis>
—Sponge gourd.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="897143455733FFD2FF1BFEF9FB7FFE2E" blockId="13.[136,1452,223,826]" box="[189,1259,367,394]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF1BFEF9FEB7FE2E" bold="true" box="[189,291,367,393]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Habitat:</emphasis>
—Waste dump sites, uncompleted buildings, unpainted fences, roadsides, fallow bush.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="897143455733FFD2FF1BFE05FE12FD0E" blockId="13.[136,1452,223,826]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF1BFE05FEC5FE0A" bold="true" box="[189,337,403,429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Description:</emphasis>
—Herb, trailing and climbing; moenoecious. 
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FCDEFE02FC3AFE09" box="[888,942,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Stem</emphasis>
herbaceous, climbing, pubescent, angular, 
<quantity id="4E36EEA05733FFD2FF2EFE21FE9CFE75" box="[136,264,439,466]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" unit="cm" value="0.44999999999999996" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.6 cm</quantity>
diam.; tendrils 3- to 4-fid, spirally coiled. 
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FD5CFE2EFCDCFE76" box="[762,840,440,465]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Leaves</emphasis>
simple, alternately arranged, petiolate, hairy on both surfaces, palmately lobed with 5 joined lobes, green, apex acute, margin dentate, 8.2–17 × 
<quantity id="4E36EEA05733FFD2FBC8FE4AFB45FE51" box="[1134,1233,476,502]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" unit="cm" value="14.0" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="9.0">9–19 cm</quantity>
; petiole cylindrical, herbaceous, 
<quantity id="4E36EEA05733FFD2FEB0FD96FEFFFDBD" box="[278,363,512,538]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" unit="cm" value="6.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="4.0">4–8 cm</quantity>
long, hairy. 
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FE5BFE69FD07FDBE" box="[509,659,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Inflorescence</emphasis>
racemose for male flowers with about 5–20 flower buds, solitary for female flowers; pedunculate, peduncle 
<quantity id="4E36EEA05733FFD2FDEEFDB2FD2DFD99" box="[584,697,548,574]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" unit="cm" value="20.5" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="10.0">10–31 cm</quantity>
long; 
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FCA3FDB5FCC2FD9A" box="[773,854,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">pedicel</emphasis>
1.5–2.0 cm long; flowers 3 × 
<quantity id="4E36EEA05733FFD2FB11FDB2FA84FD99" box="[1207,1296,548,574]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" unit="cm" value="8.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="8.0">8–9 cm</quantity>
; calyx with 5 green, free sepals; corolla with 5 yellow, free imbricate petals, pubescent on both surfaces, 3–5 × 
<quantity id="4E36EEA05733FFD2FB61FDDEFA88FDC5" box="[1223,1308,584,610]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" unit="cm" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 cm</quantity>
, androecium parts 5. 
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF43FDFAFE8BFD22" box="[229,287,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Fruit</emphasis>
pepos, cylindrical, green when fresh, brown and paper-like when dry, produces sponge bearing many seeds. 
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF75FD19FE9CFD0E" box="[211,264,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Seed</emphasis>
flat, black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="897143455733FFD2FF1BFD25FBF5FD56" blockId="13.[136,1452,223,826]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF1BFD25FEDDFD6A" bold="true" box="[189,329,691,717]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Location in</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="39A649185733FFD2FEF5FD25FBC9FD56" location="Eastern Obolo" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Akwa Ibom">
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FEF5FD25FD9DFD69" bold="true" box="[339,521,691,718]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
<collectingRegion id="4B0A8DA75733FFD2FEF5FD25FE72FD69" box="[339,486,691,718]" country="Nigeria" name="Akwa Ibom" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Akwa Ibom</collectingRegion>
:—
</emphasis>
Ini, Essien Udim, Oruk Anam, Obot Akara, Ikot Ekpene, Ibiono, Uyo, Ibesikpo Asutan, Nsit Atai, Nsit Ubium, Mkpat Enin, Ikot Abasi, Oron, Mbo, and 
<location id="8C11159E5733FFD2FC1EFD4EFBC9FD56" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0167F2535733FFD2FF2EFF08FE53FC9D:8C11159E5733FFD2FC1EFD4EFBC9FD56" box="[952,1117,727,754]" name="Eastern Obolo" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" stateProvince="Akwa Ibom">Eastern Obolo</location>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="897143455733FFD2FF1BFD6DFE53FC9D" blockId="13.[136,1452,223,826]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis id="BBBA9F575733FFD2FF1BFD6DFEF8FCB2" bold="true" box="[189,364,763,789]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Abundance:—</emphasis>
It existed in 100% of the sampling areas, where it was abundant in 73%, frequent in 21%, and rare in 6% of the sampling areas.
</paragraph>
